 archaeological curiosities. The book follows the exemplary careers of two objects—the so-called “Stone Women” and the kurgan, or burial mound—and the attention paid to them by Russian and Soviet archaeologists, writers, artists, and filmmakers, for whom these artifacts served as resources for modernist art and letters and as arenas for a contest between vying conceptions of Russian art, culture, and history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aArchaeologyxRussia (Federation). 0aArchaeologyzRussia (Federation) 0aArchaeologyzRussia (Federation). 0aExcavations (Archaeology)xEurasia. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zEurasia. 0aModernism (Aesthetics)xRussia (Federation). 0aModernism (Aesthetics)zRussia (Federation) 0aModernism (Aesthetics)zRussia (Federation). 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015z978311068814608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2015z97831110235570 cprintz978161811441940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978161811442640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781618114426423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781618114426/original  a978-3-11-068814-6  Academic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015c2008d2015  a978-3-11-102355-7  Academic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK